Huge thank you to the rescuers in this video 💚 Unfortunately not all turtles are this lucky. Once trapped in a net, turtles are dragged through the water with no access to the surface to breathe, causing them to drown. It's estimated that some 4,600 sea turtles are killed by fishing nets and hooks every year in U.S. waters alone ☹️
Video via @thedodo

node.text:
Moray eels 🖐
Fun fact: 
- A moray eel appears dangerous because it continually exposes its mouth and teeth. This action, however, is not a hostile gesture, but simply the way an eel breathes. Morays have large mouths and powerful jaws with a vice-like grip. Most species have sharp, thin teeth that protrude from the upper and lower jaws, and sometimes from the roof of the mouth. The teeth point backwards to prevent slippery prey from escaping. 
- Because most moray eels have low dorsal (top) fins and lack pectoral and pelvic fins, they do not have a great amount of lateral stability. It is not uncommon to see moray eels lying or drifting on their sides or even upside down.
📸 @espekanela

Did you know that Octopuses have 3 hearts, 9 brains and blue blood? 🐙🤯

Why does an octopus have 9 brains?

Octopuses have 9 brains because, in addition to the central brain, each of 8 arms has a mini-brain that allows it to act independently.

Actual footage and A Rare Sighting of a Glass Octopus Reveals its Nearly Transparent Membrane in Extraordinary Detail⁣
⁣
On a 34-day expedition around the Phoenix Islands Archipelago, marine scientists from the Schmidt Ocean Institute captured exceptionally rare footage of the elusive glass octopus. With a speckled, iridescent membrane, the aquatic animal is almost entirely transparent—only its optic nerve, eyes, and digestive tract are visible to humans—and sightings like these are so infrequent that scientists previously resorted to studying the species only after pulling it from the stomachs of its predators.⁣
⁣
Source: thisiscolossal.com⁣
Video by: @schmidtocean⁣

Turtle cleaning! 🛀 🏝 Why is this done?
A build up of algae and other waste can lead to skin disease so it’s important that we clean their shells often! 
The brown and green on the turtles are a mix of algae and water scales. ***This turtle is being cleaned at a marine rescue centre / do not try this!! In the wild this is done by cleaner fish 🐟
~
Video by @ogasawara_marine_centre
